Sure, hard to cram all the worldbuilding and backstory into a short post but I'll damn well try

>hard sci-fi
>~400 years in the future
>AI + humans coexist, AI based on human brains, have emotion, goals, but are different enough from humans that it has many societal implications
>humanity expanded throughout solar system, Mars, Europa, Titan all terraformed/massive habitation, McKendree cylinders everywhere
>Breakthrough in FTL tech, variant of Alcubierre drive utilizing Woodward effect for negative mass-density particles needed.
>Get on average 1-2 light-years per day dependent on ship size, reactor power, etc.
>Massive rush to explore so govt funds massive wide-scale exploration project, think the age of discovery but in the stars
>over 1000 volunteer explorers, 1 each in a ship + an AI
>travel varying in distance between 200 - 5000 light-years away
>protag is on the edge of the project, 4500 light-years out, 10 year travel time spent in cryo
>as soon as they exit FTL, discover signals from an unknown source
>eventually find planet location, obviously not as advanced as humanity as signals emanating from one planet, other clues
>get closer, let out some scout drones to get a good look
>turns out species nuked themselves, AI + protag dumbfounded, don't know what to do
>drones find signs of life on planet, population estimated at a couple hundred thousand max

From there, you have the protag + AI contemplating what to do, if they should just return home and let the government know, or try and help. Because of 20+ years until anyone would get back, they decide to help to ensure survival of the species until they leave and get help. Lots of exploration, science, tense moments ensue in the quest to learn more about the species (language, culture, etc.) Obviously, fuzzy wahmen come into play, and fun times aplenty.

This is the first piece I've ever written, so it very well could be complete shit, but I am having fun with it, and that's all that matters
